{{Main|Church of Cyric}}
The Cyricist church was hated across Toril with good reason: Cyric's church was pledged to spread strife and work murder everywhere in order to make folk believe in and fear the Dark Sun. It supported cruel rulers and indulged fostered fear and intrigue while avoiding the spread of outright war. The church was often beset by internal feuds and backstabbing for some time before eventually waning. Many outside the church viewed it as a twisted den of madness, trickery, and death. Cyricist clergy condemned this outlook, preferring to see their religion as one of enlightenment. It purportedly revealed that all societal bonds of friendship, family, and love were nothing but ties that always withered away, and were therefore useless, weak, and pitiful.

Cyric's [[clerics]] prayed for spells at night, after moonrise, and often trained as [[rogues]] or [[assassins]]. They celebrated few holy days and did not acknowledge the date of his ascension to divinity, because it coincide with that of Midnight. Whenever a temple acquired something, or someone, important enough to be sacrificed, its high priest declared a Day of the Dark Sun to signify the holiness of the event. Eclipses were considered holy occasions, and were accompanied by feasts, fervent prayers, and bloody sacrifices.

In addition to the worshipers Cyric claimed during his ascension, he also garnered those of the [[Church of Leira|Leiran]] faith after slaying the Lady of Deception. [[Tethyr]]ian cultists of Ao that remained unaware of their true divine patron, and renegade [[githyanki]] that forewent worship of their [[lich]]-queen.<ref name=Poly159.KLQ-p29">{{Cite polyhedron/159/Incursion: Knights of the Lich-Queen|29}}

History.The Prisoner:
{{Quote|The white queen is troubled by can't say why. The black queen hates the white and gives the assassin a black cloak. The assassin steals up on the white queen. She can't see him gliding through the shadows. The sword screams. The white queen falls. Her city falls.|[[Yaphyll]]'s prophecy about Mystra, Shar, and Cyric.}}
In the {{YearlinkName|1373}}, a new and more capable champion of Cyric named [[Zasian Menz]] arose to carry out his will throughout the Realms. Zasian managed to open a pathway to [[Celestia]] from the [[City of Brass]], a plot that claimed twelve years of the priest's life. In the years that followed, Cyric forged an alliance with the goddess [[Shar]], working together to weaken Mystra's hold over the Weave and lessen her influence in the Realms.

Over a decade later, in the {{YearlinkName|1384}}, Cyric unleashed his wrath on Helm by orchestrating his death at the hands of Tyr.{{Cite dragon/381/Channel Divinity: Champions of Torm|91}}

The [[1385 DR|following year]], Cyric's priest Zasian freed the Sharran 'shadow mystic' [[Kashada]] from imprisonment in Celestia. Kashada was in fact an aspect of the goddess Shar, the Goddess of Night. Shar had manipulated Cyric's Zasian to help her supplant the Weave with her own [[Shadow Weave]]. and Shar distracted the god Azuth long enough for Cyric to recover his arcane staff. Cyric used Azuth's ''[[Old Staff]]'' to finally murder Mystra, and exacted revenge upon his former companion and one-time friend. Mystra's death wrecked the bonds that held together the Weave, and brought about the Spellplague, a calamitous event that was felt across the multiverse.{{Cite dungeon/181/Campaign Workshop: Hero Battle: Elminster|39}}

In retaliation for his murder of Mystra, [[Lathander]], Tyr, and Sune trapped Cyric in the Supreme Throne for 1000 years. It was believed by some that Cyric foresaw his own imprisonment and formulated a plot to forge a key that would grant his escape.{{Cite digital book/Spinner of Lies||chp=24}} This did not come to pass however, and Cyric's power continually waned over the next century. The worship of Bane flourished in its place, as the faith of the Black Lord became the state religion in the realm of [[Thay]].

Cyric would not appear in the mortal Realms for over a century, and even then only as a mere manifestation. In the {{YearlinkName|1486}}, during the world-shaping [[Second Sundering]], Cyric ordered his long-faithful servant and newly designated chosen Malik to foil Shar's faithful from securing the ''[[Eye of Gruumsh]]'' to initiate the [[Cycle of Night]] on Toril. While Malik and his companions‚Äîchosen of Helm, Sune, and [[Siamorphe]]‚Äîventured through the [[Chondalwood]], Cyric manifested before Malik as the visage of a skull in a dead tree. The imprisoned god ordered Malik to slay his fellows at their exact moment of triumph.
